		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Initiative: Great Addition or Gaming Nightmare<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.85)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 23, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
It’s been quite a while since I’ve written an article, so I may be a bit rusty, but I’ll just get right to the point.<br />
<br />
	I’ve been thinking about the new gaming concept, Initiative. It’s gotten me thinking about a lot of new ideas that could greater improve upon the strategy of the game. Since the competitive players out there dislike the somewhat random luck factor involved with LOTR, this would be a be a good thing….or, at least, it would seem to be.<br />
<br />
I know it’s a bit early to be getting ideas about an idea that has hardly been spoiled, so I’m primarily basing this on cards that have been spoiled. <br />
<br />
The concept is based on hand size, so it would be logical to say that it would be controlled mostly by free peoples. The concept, in theory, is good. It discourages emptying your entire hand. Before, there was no reason to keep cards, playing everything was to your full advantage and there was no reason to keep cards in your hand, especially if they were cheap. Now, you’ll not only give yourself an advantage, but keep the shadow player from pulling off powerful abilities on you.<br />
<br />
First off, in general, it seems the Free Peoples initiative advantage rewards you (assuming you’ve kept your hand large enough through the fellowship phase) by giving you a chance to still empty your hand, but outside the fellowship phase. Here’s an example:<br />
<br />
.Gondorian Merchant<br />
Gondor. <br />
Ally. Home 3K. Man.<br />
Cost:1<br />
Strength:6<br />
Vitality:1<br />
Maneuver: If you have initiative, discard 2 cards <br />
from hand to make the site number of minion +2<br />
until the regroup phase.<br />
<br />
You’ve probably seen it already as it was one of the first cards spoiled. Notice that this action is not fellowship, but still lets you get rid of those cards you were holding onto for the sole purpose of keeping initiative. This will also let you bypass certain shadow cards utilizing initiative in the shadow phase such as Attea (more on him later). Notice, also that this is the first time the FPs player has been able to tamper with the site number of minions before the skirmish phase. Since it works in Maneuver, this will open opportunities for using combos such as What Are They? and Eregion Trails. Want a minion dead? This is the way to do it.<br />
<br />
Another card<br />
<br />
.Smeagol, Hurried Guide<br />
 Gollum(FP)<br />
 Companion<br />
 Cost:0<br />
 Strength:3<br />
 Vitality:4<br />
 To play, add a burden. Skirmish: If you have initiative, <br />
discard 2 cards from hand. Smeagol may not be overwhelmed<br />
unless his strength is tripled.<br />
<br />
While not generally helpful, we know how easy it is for a weakling like Smeagol to die and if want him around, this is a logical choice for a smeagol, especially combined with Sam, Nice Sensible Hobbit. Once again, we see the discard trick working again. If you didn’t get rid of them before and still want to, this is an excellent way to do it.<br />
<br />
Remember the memories of Christmas time and you’ve got gifts all under the tree. You beg your parents to let you open a few of them early, but they tell you that you’ve got to wait until Dec.25th. Fellowship dumping is like opening your gift early. You get what you want (in this case, cards out of your hand), but the fun ends there. There’s nothing after and you’re stuck waiting for more. Just wait it out with your hand and you’ll get what you want with surplus. <br />
<br />
But, wait. Isn’t the point of initiative to have cards in hand instead of discarding them? Doesn’t this jeopardize your position to shadow initiative? The answer is yes. Generally, your concern over this matter will greatly depend on whether or not your opponent is utilizing initiative. It seems that minions from all cultures in ROTK will feature cards utilizing it, so if you are facing those decks, taking appropriate precaution can be strongly advantageous.  What’s to be done? Well, you can utilize cards that allow drawing cards outside the fellowship or in. Drawing cards in the fellowship will give you a larger hand and give you more of the reward, while filtering your hand. Drawing outside is usually less costly, but can still give you desired protection. Here’s a good example.<br />
<br />
.Hope Comes<br />
 Elven<br />
 Condition. Support Area.<br />
 Cost:2<br />
 To play, spot 2 elves. Response: If an [elven] skirmish <br />
 event is played, discard this condition to draw 3 cards.<br />
<br />
You can still filter your hand with cards like Smeagol, but you can bypass hazardous risks until you can pacify it. Another somewhat interesting strategy is using the new Merry. Interestingly enough, unlike his predecessors, he goes back into your hand after use. The game text by itself is well worth it, but this may also provide you with a small bit of extra security as it will be an extra card in your hand and may allow you to play one more card than you thought.<br />
<br />
Essentially, there is nothing wrong, in summary, with FPs initiative rewards. They are not overly powerful, but still provide an incentive not to empty your hand all at once.<br />
<br />
Shadow initiative, on the other hand, can get rough around the edges. Naturally ,the advantages of Shadow initiative will be more powerful than the FPs advantages because they have much less control over it than the FPs player. <br />
<br />
However, there are ample ways for the shadow player to control the FPs hand, as well. In fact, one anonymous card from the set had this text:<br />
<br />
Regroup: Remove (3) and spot a [raider] man to place a [raider] token here. While there are 3 [raider] tokens here, the shadow player has initiative, regardless of the Free Peoples player’s hand.<br />
<br />
The cost seems very high, but with Southrons, you could accumulate 3 tokens on this in one turn. I’m sure you’re familiar with the various methods. Once set up, the only hope the FPs player has to escape constant risk is to get rid of the condition. From this, we see that it is at least one way to manipulate initiative without having to tamper with your opponent’s hand. <br />
<br />
That is one choice. The other is, obviously, tampering with your opponent’s hand. There are several ways of going about it. Timing is the key. When do most of your shadow cards utilize initiative? If you like to abuse nasties like-<br />
<br />
.Ulaire Attea, Wraith on Wings<br />
 Ringwraith<br />
 Minion. Nazgul.<br />
 Cost:6<br />
 Strength:12<br />
 Vitality:3<br />
 Fierce. Shadow: If you have initiative, exert Ulaire Attea and spot another [ringwraith] minion to add a burden.<br />
<br />
-then you’d want to use cards filtering the hand during or before the shadow phase. Tower of Barad-dur is one way to go. If you play Sauron with it, then it can make an interesting impression. 4 of them will likely give you initiative every turn and even a few will cripple their options. Knowing that you could drop a beastie like Attea and give them an automatic 2 burdens will put pressure on them. As you may know, putting pressure on your opponent in this game can work to your advantage. Another deadly tool, we all know too well, the old skool Palantir. Throw a few isengard dudes into the mix, spend a bit of twilight and you have initiative. Now what usefulness this card had practically doubles with initiative…and there have already been complaints about it being overpowered before initiative came into the picture. This is where the scene might turn negative.<br />
<br />
Let’s say you try out an isy men with Nazgul deck. It’s actually a powerful combo (read my isy men article). This would allow use of the Palantir, right? Well, it hardly seems like much to worry about. So they made a good play, they deserve to crunch you with 2 burdens. It hopefully won’t be game breaking; but when cards like this are thrown into the mix:<br />
<br />
.Out of Sight and Shot<br />
 Condition. Support Area.<br />
 Cost:1<br />
 To play, spot a Nazgul. Each time a companion is played, the Free Peoples player must exert a companion. Shadow: Spot a Nazgul and discard this condition to play a Nazgul from your discard pile.<br />
<br />
If you don’t see where I’m going with this, here’s the pattern. Palantir, Attea exerts down, you get rid of him, then play him again with the condition, starting an endless cycle. With enough copies and aids like the new Witch King, you could possibly play him 8 times in one game, enough to corrupt Frodo. It would be fairly easy, almost too easy. This combo may be trouble; and if Attea doesn’t cut it, then you can rely on his partner in crime:<br />
<br />
Ulaire Nertea, Black-Mantled Wraith<br />
Minion. Nazgul.<br />
Cost:4<br />
Strength:9<br />
Vitality:2<br />
Regroup: If you have initiative, discard Ulaire Nertea<br />
to add a burden. <br />
<br />
To utilize this guy, cards like Desperate Defense of the Ring can be helpful as well, since the text is activated after shadow. Then, of course, there is Nelya, who is the anti ring-bound nazzie this time (it was Nertea in EoF).<br />
<br />
Judge for yourself. Is initiative a great addition to the game, as it should be, or can it be abused and turned into a gaming nightmare? One thing is for sure; we’ll find out when the ROTK cards start rolling out and the decks start being thrown together.<br />
 <br />
